The "Bedrock_Surface_Elevation" is a 110 meter resolution DEM compiled by the Iowa Geological and Water survey and approximates throughout the state the surface elevation of Iowa's bedrock.  ESRI's ArcGIS 9.3.1 Spatial Analyst "Minus" function was utilized to subtract the raster layer "Bedrock_Surface_Elevation" from the raster layer "NED_FT" to calculate the approximate depth to bedrock at any given area in Iowa.  STEP 2:  CORRECTING NEGATIVE ELEVATIONAL VALUES  The resulting raster layer contained areas with negative depth values.  These negative values are inherent when subtracting relatively large resolution data (in this case 110 meter) from relatively smaller resolution data (in this case 30 meters).  To correct the pixels with negative values, it was first assumed that they represented areas that are at or very near the land's surface.  Thus a depth value of "0" was assigned to these areas.  This was carried out by creating a SQL expression in ESRI's ArcGIS 9.3.1 Spatial Analyst Raster Calculator where any depth values less than '0' were assigned a value of '0'.   </procdesc>     <proccont>      <cntinfo>       <cntpos>Geologist</cntpos>       <cntvoice>319-335-1575</cntvoice>       <cntinst>Ray Anderson [Raymond.Anderson@dnr.iowa.gov] Brian Witzke [Brian.Witzke@dnr.iowa.gov] Bill Bunker [Bill.Bunker@dnr.iowa.gov]</cntinst>       <cntorgp>        <cntorg>Iowa Geological & Water Survey, DNR</cntorg>       </cntorgp>      </cntinfo>     </proccont>    </procstep>    <srcinfo>     <srccite>      <citeinfo>       <title>GEOSAM: Iowa's Geologic & Sample Tracking Program</title>       <onlink>http://www.igsb.uiowa.edu/webapps/Geosam</onlink>      </citeinfo>     </srccite>    </srcinfo>    <procstep>     <procdesc>CONVERSION OF THE BEDROCK CONTOUR LINES TO A GRID:  (1) Attempts to convert the contour lines to a gird were not very satisfying because of the number of vertices on many of the contour lines, and only a tin could be generated which resulted in a very stepped surface of relief.   Therefore, a third party product, ET Geo Wizards conversion of polyline to points (vertices selected) was utilized to generate a point file of all vertices of all the contour lines.  This created a point shapefile of over 4,000,000 points of elevation.  (2)  Then using the TopoToRaster tool from ArcGis  3D Analyst Tools this point file was selected as the Feature Layer, Elevation as the Field, and Point Elevation as the Type.  Additionally the state border of Iowa was added as a Feature Layer and Boundary was selected as the Type.  A 110 meter Output cell size was selected for generation of the grid.  All other defaults were left alone.  (3) The resultant grid was then generated from this approach.</procdesc>     <proccont>      <cntinfo>       <cntorgp>        <cntorg>Iowa Geological & Water Survey</cntorg>        <cntper>Andy
